title HAWM0 boots real, KVM-accelerated, in 11 seconds -- the ladder's first checkable rung
prompt Keaton shared a screenshot of a real host-terminal run of tools/hawm0_boot_onpath_host.rish -- a clean GREEN close, sys.boot_completed after 11s, device identity read back as sdk_gphone64_x86_64 / android=16 / abi=x86_64 with ro.kernel.qemu=1.
think Read the screenshot's own printed evidence line by line rather than assuming success from the final GREEN line alone: kvm present -> emulator+AVD present -> no stray emulator -> launched with -accel kvm -> adb attached after 10s of polling -> boot_completed after 11s (well inside the 120s ceiling the worker script allows) -> device props read back clean. Every precondition and every poll step this same jail's own earlier dry-run had only proven syntactically now has a real, host-side result behind it. ro.kernel.qemu=1 is the one property that actually distinguishes a real KVM-accelerated boot from a software (TCG) fallback that would still eventually finish -- named this explicitly rather than treating "it booted" alone as proof of acceleration.
think Recorded the result as a genuine status change, not a footnote: the living spec's own register line at the top of the doc said "HAWM0 is checked-and-honestly-blocked... everything else is horizon" as of the last edit -- updated it to name HAWM0 as checkable/green outright, since a register claim that is stale the moment a real result lands is exactly the kind of drift docs-implementation-sync exists to catch. Updated the rung table's own State cell fully (not just appended a note) so a reader scanning the table alone sees the real, current status rather than an outdated "setup landed, boot handed off" description that was true an hour ago and no longer is.
think Named the immediate downstream effect rather than only the fact itself: HAWM1 (Sala broadcaster inside the AVD) was gated on HAWM0's own boot -- with HAWM0 now real, HAWM1 is unblocked on its own gate for the first time, which changes what the next reachable step on this ladder actually is. Did not open or start HAWM1 itself; only named that its gate condition now holds.
think Kept the honest register intact rather than letting the excitement of a real GREEN inflate the claim: added one explicit sentence to the "honest register" paragraph naming that this GREEN close still proves stock AOSP/Android under KVM, not GrapheneOS itself -- the same discipline the doc already carried, now anchored to a real result instead of only a hypothetical one.
obs This is the first rung on the whole GrapheneOS/Pixel ladder (opened 20260715.163500, five days prior) to move from a design/horizon register to a checkable, green, machine-witnessed one -- worth naming plainly as a real milestone for the thread, not merely another dated bullet.
